<HEADLINE>
THREE MORE BODIES FOUND AT MILITARY HELICOPTER CRASH SITE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kaohsiung,  April 4 (CNA) 04/04/07  12:20:17
</P>
<P>
Minister of National Defense Lee Jye offered his condolences for
the death of eight military officers at the Kaohsiung Military
General Hospital Wednesday after the bodies of three people
reported missing in the crash of a military helicopter were found
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Rescue personnel found the three bodies in the early morning near
the crashed UH-1H helicopter and the radio Public Radio System
transmission tower that it had hit. The bodies were later
identified as those of the three reported missing of eight
military officers aboard the aircraft. The burned remains of the
other five were found at the crash site earlier.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter crashed into the transmission tower in the
Chungliao mountainous region of Chishan Township in the southern
county of Kaohsiung Tuesday afternoon while performing a
surveillance training mission, killing all eight senior officers
from an army airborne cavalry brigade, one of the most elite
military units.
</P>
<P>
The deceased include Col. Chen Ming-tung, head of the Airborne
Cavalry Brigade 601, who was expected to be promoted to major
general soon; Maj. Lin Kuo-chun, deputy chief of the brigade; Lt.
Col. Ma Wen-pin, head of an attack battalion; Lt. Col. Lai Yu-
hung, a chief staff officer; Maj. Chu Chih-hua, a company
commander; Maj. Liu Tien-shun, pilot; Capt. Wu Ming-chung, a co-
pilot; and Sgt. Maj. Luo Ming-hua, a chief technician. By
Elizabeth Hsu)
</P>
